src/
├── controllers/     # HTTP handlers only — no business logic
├── routes/          # Router definitions — wire controllers to endpoints
├── models/          # TypeScript types and interfaces
├── middleware/      # Express middleware
├── repositories/    # All database access — never query DB outside here
├── utils/       
└── config.ts        # Environment variables — never use process.env directly

## Naming Conventions
- Files: `camelCase.ts` (e.g. `userController.ts`, `userModel.ts`)
- Classes/Types/Interfaces: `PascalCase` (e.g. `UserRepository`)
- Functions/Variables: `camelCase` (e.g. `getUserById`)
- Routes: plural lowercase (e.g. `/users`, `/auth`)

## Architecture Patterns

### Route Registration
Routes are registered through a main API router in `app.ts`:
```typescript
app.use('/api', apiRouter)
// apiRouter registers: /auth, /users etc.
```

### Error Handling
Controllers use try/catch and forward to global error middleware:
```typescript
try {
  // handler logic
} catch (error) {
  next(error)
}
```
Custom error classes live in `utils/errors.ts` extending the base `Error` class.

### Repository Pattern
All database queries live in repositories. Controllers never access the database directly — they call repository methods only.

### Business Logic
Controllers handle HTTP concerns only. Extract any reusable logic to `utils/helpers.ts`. Simple one-off transformations can live in controllers but should not query the database or call external services.

## Environment Variables
Never access `process.env` directly. Always import from `src/config.ts`:
```typescript
import { config } from './config'
config.PORT
```

## What NOT To Do
- Never put database queries in controllers
- Never access `process.env` directly — use `config`
- Never put business logic in repositories
- Never skip the error middleware — always call `next(error)` in catch blocks